replies.bodyText:
In existing code, Topics.remove(Node) calls the below code
        n.fire(WhatHappened.removed);
        childChanged(WhatHappened.childRemoved, n);

while Topic.fire(WhatHappened.removed) calls
parent.childChanged(what, this);

Which will cause the parent being called childChanged twice, once with removed and once with childRemoved
The expected behavior is, when calling Node.remove() or Topics.remove(child), the child node get 'removed' event once and parent node get 'childRemoved' event once, and the node is removed from parent's children. Here I choose to let child invoke parent.childChanged(event).

